{"title_page": "Hugh Lyon Tennent", "text_new": "[[File:The grave of Hugh Lyon Tennent, Dean Cemetery, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|330px|The grave of Hugh Lyon Tennent, Dean Cemetery, Edinburgh]]\n'''Hugh Lyon Tennent''' (11 May 1817 \u2013 22 January 1874) was a Scottish [[advocate]] and pioneer photographer. He is sometimes recorded as '''Hugh Lyon Tennant'''.\n\n==Life==\n\nTennent was born in [[Edinburgh]] on 11 May 1817, the son of  Margaret Rodger Lyon (1794\u20131867) and Patrick Tennant [[Writer to the Signet|WS]] (1782\u20131872), living at 107 George Street.<ref>Edinburgh Post Office Directory 1817</ref> His older brother [[Robert Tennent (photographer)|Robert]] had similar interests. His family were related to the [[Glasgow]] [[Tennents]] of brewery fame.\n\nHe followed in his father's career and studied law, qualifying as an advocate in 1840. He became Sheriff Substitute of [[Lanarkshire]] in 1853 and Sheriff Substitute of [[Greenock]] in 1856, remaining there for the rest of his life.\n\nFrom 1843 he was a member of the [[Edinburgh Calotype Club]] along with his brother and other noted members such as [[David Brewster]] and [[John Cay]].<ref>The Photography of Victorian Scotland, Roddy Simpson</ref> Tennent was one of the youngest members. He also joined the [[Photographic Society of Scotland]] in 1856. He took many early photographs of the Tennents [[Wellpark Brewery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/pencilsoflight/biography.cfm?photographer=Tennent,%20Hugh%20Lyon%20(1817-1874)|title=Tennent, Hugh Lyon (1817-1874)|website=National Library of Scotland|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref><ref>Encyclopaedia of Nineteenth Century Photography, John Hannavy</ref>\n\nTennent was a keen sailor and made a trip of the [[Outer Hebrides|Western Isles]] in 1838.<ref>National Library of Scotland shelf reference acc.12071</ref> He was a member of the Royal Clyde Yacht Club, and in later life he had a 15-ton yacht named \"Seaward\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.luminous-lint.com/app/photographer/Hugh_Lyon__Tennent/A/|title=Luminous-Lint - Photographer - Hugh Lyon Tennent|last=Griffiths|first=Alan|website=www.luminous-lint.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n\nA noted philanthropist, he promoted the Discharged Prisoners Aid Society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/pencilsoflight/biography.cfm?photographer=Tennent,%20Hugh%20Lyon%20(1817-1874)|title=Tennent, Hugh Lyon (1817-1874)|website=National Library of Scotland|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n\nHe died in [[Edinburgh]] on 22 January 1874. He is buried in [[Dean Cemetery]] in western Edinburgh. The small simple marker stone lies in the first northern extension not far from his brother Robert.\n\n==Family==\n\nIn 1855 he was married to Agnes Halsey (1833\u20131913).<ref>https://www.ancestry.co.uk/boards/surnames.tennent/13.1.1.1/mb.ashx</ref> They had nine children<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.co.uk/genealogy/records/hugh-lyon-tennant_91118127|title=Hugh Lyon Tennant 1817-1874 - Ancestry.co.uk|website=www.ancestry.co.uk|language=en-us|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref> including Henry Edward Tennent (1861-1873) who is buried with them.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tennent, Hugh Lyon}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1874 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Scottish photographers]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:The grave of Hugh Lyon Tennent, Dean Cemetery, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|330px|The grave of Hugh Lyon Tennent, Dean Cemetery, Edinburgh]]\n'''Hugh Lyon Tennent''' (11 May 1817 \u2013 22 January 1874) was a Scottish [[advocate]] and pioneer photographer. He is sometimes recorded as '''Hugh Lyon Tennant'''.\n\n==Life==\n\nTennent was born in [[Edinburgh]] on 11 May 1817, the son of  Margaret Rodger Lyon (1794\u20131867) and Patrick Tennant [[Writer to the Signet|WS]] (1782\u20131872), living at 107 George Street.<ref>Edinburgh Post Office Directory 1817</ref> His older brother [[Robert Tennent (photographer)|Robert]] had similar interests. His family were related to the [[Glasgow]] [[Tennents]] of brewery fame.\n\nHe followed in his father's career and studied law, qualifying as an advocate in 1840. He became Sheriff Substitute of [[Lanarkshire]] in 1853 and Sheriff Substitute of [[Greenock]] in 1856, remaining there for the rest of his life.\n\nFrom 1843 he was a member of the [[Edinburgh Calotype Club]] along with his brother and other noted members such as [[David Brewster]] and [[John Cay]].<ref>The Photography of Victorian Scotland, Roddy Simpson</ref> Tennent was one of the youngest members. He also joined the [[Photographic Society of Scotland]] in 1856. He took many early photographs of the Tennents [[Wellpark Brewery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/pencilsoflight/biography.cfm?photographer=Tennent,%20Hugh%20Lyon%20(1817-1874)|title=Tennent, Hugh Lyon (1817-1874)|website=National Library of Scotland|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref><ref>Encyclopaedia of Nineteenth Century Photography, John Hannavy</ref>\n\nTennent was a keen sailor and made a trip of the [[Outer Hebrides|Western Isles]] in 1838.<ref>National Library of Scotland shelf reference acc.12071</ref> He was a member of the Royal Clyde Yacht Club, and in later life he had a 15-ton yacht named \"Seaward\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.luminous-lint.com/app/photographer/Hugh_Lyon__Tennent/A/|title=Luminous-Lint - Photographer - Hugh Lyon Tennent|last=Griffiths|first=Alan|website=www.luminous-lint.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n\nA noted philanthropist he promoted the Discharged Prisoners Aid Society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/pencilsoflight/biography.cfm?photographer=Tennent,%20Hugh%20Lyon%20(1817-1874)|title=Tennent, Hugh Lyon (1817-1874)|website=National Library of Scotland|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n\nHe died in [[Edinburgh]] on 22 January 1874. He is buried in [[Dean Cemetery]] in western Edinburgh. The small simple marker stone lies in the first northern extension not far from his brother Robert.\n\n==Family==\n\nIn 1855 he was married to Agnes Halsey (1833\u20131913).<ref>https://www.ancestry.co.uk/boards/surnames.tennent/13.1.1.1/mb.ashx</ref> They had nine children<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.co.uk/genealogy/records/hugh-lyon-tennant_91118127|title=Hugh Lyon Tennant 1817-1874 - Ancestry.co.uk|website=www.ancestry.co.uk|language=en-us|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref> including Henry Edward Tennent (1861-1873) who is buried with them.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tennent, Hugh Lyon}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1874 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Scottish photographers]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Julia H. Mach", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Lyon_Tennent"}
