{"title_page": "Yolk of the Golden Egg", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Yolk of the Golden Egg\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Dandi Wind]]\n| cover      = Yolk of the Golden Egg.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 23, 2008\n| recorded   = 2008\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Post-industrial music|Post-industrial]], [[electropunk]], [[electronica]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Summer Lovers Unlimited Music]], Tell Me Records\n| producer   = [[Dandi Wind|Szam Findlay]]\n| prev_title = [[Concrete Igloo]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Yolk of the Golden Egg''''' is the second full-length album by Canadian [[post-industrial music|post-industrial]] band [[Dandi Wind]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/59834/dandi-wind-lays-golden-egg |title=Dandi Wind Lays Golden Egg |magazine=[[Chart (magazine)|Chartattack.com]] |accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trashmenagerie.com/blog/2007/07/17/dandi-wind-%E2%80%93-refined-chaos/ |title=DANDI WIND \u2013 REFINED CHAOS |publisher=Trash Menagerie |accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref>  All songs were written and produced by [[Dandi Wind|Szam Findlay]], with [[Dandi Wind|Dandilion Wind Opaine]] providing vocals.\n\n==Track listing==\n(all songs written by Szam Findlay)\n# Battle Of Verdun\n# A Lifetime\n# Adolescent\n# Powerball\n# Cocoon\n# Baying Of The Hounds\n# Silver Lying\n# Midget Palace\n# Yo Pinok\n# Johatsu\n# Foundling Circle\n# Dance Of The Paralytic\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110806231254/http://www.nfb.ca/film/yolk_of_the_golden_egg/ Promotional Video by John Londono]\n\n[[Category:Dandi Wind albums]]\n[[Category:2008 albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-electronic-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Yolk of the Golden Egg\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Dandi Wind]]\n| cover      = Yolk of the Golden Egg.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 23, 2008\n| recorded   = 2008\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Post-industrial music|Post-industrial]], [[electropunk]], [[electronica]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Summer Lovers Unlimited Music]], Tell Me Records\n| producer   = [[Dandi Wind|Szam Findlay]]\n| prev_title = [[Concrete Igloo]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Yolk of the Golden Egg''''' is the second full-length album by Canadian [[post-industrial music|post-industrial]] band [[Dandi Wind]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/59834/dandi-wind-lays-golden-egg |title=Dandi Wind Lays Golden Egg |magazine=[[Chart (magazine)|Chartattack.com]] |accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trashmenagerie.com/blog/2007/07/17/dandi-wind-%E2%80%93-refined-chaos/ |title=DANDI WIND \u2013 REFINED CHAOS |publisher=Trash Menagerie |accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref>  All songs were written and produced by [[Dandi Wind|Szam Findlay]], with [[Dandi Wind|Dandilion Wind Opaine]] providing vocals.\n\n==Track listing==\n(all songs written by Szam Findlay)\n# Battle Of Verdun\n# A Lifetime\n# Adolescent\n# Powerball\n# Cocooon\n# Baying Of The Hounds\n# Silver Lying\n# Midget Palace\n# Yo Pinok\n# Johatsu\n# Foundling Circle\n# Dance Of The Paralytic\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110806231254/http://www.nfb.ca/film/yolk_of_the_golden_egg/ Promotional Video by John Londono]\n\n[[Category:Dandi Wind albums]]\n[[Category:2008 albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-electronic-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cocooon->Cocoon -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yolk_of_the_Golden_Egg"}
{"title_page": "1916 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''1916 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season''' was the 8th year of the organisation. All grades were dramatically affected by players enlisting in the war efforts. Prior to the commencement of the season it was stated in the management committee meeting that 487 players in the Auckland district alone had committed to the war effort.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Big Entry of Teams\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLVII| issue=107\n| date = 1916-05-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19160505.2.101\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref> Teams were filled with older players and juniors. The [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] senior team as was noted at their committee meeting featured \u201conly three men eligible for military service..., and these were all registered and waiting to be called up. Of the remainder, six were married men with families, two were permanent force men, and four were under military age\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Otahuhu Club\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LIII |issue=16225\n| date = 1916-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160510.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\nDespite this attendances were still good, with the mid season match between [[City Rovers]] and [[Grafton Athletic]] at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] attracting 3,000 spectators. While the Round 7 fixtures at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] drew the same number of spectators and 4,000 attending the round 8 matches. All the gate takings were donated to the Children's Hospital Ward Equipment Fund.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =City Defeats North Shore\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LIII |issue=16277\n| date = 1916-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160710.2.79\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref> The final round saw over 4,000 attend Victoria Park where [[City Rovers]] won the title with a 14 points to 10 win over [[Grafton Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Senior Championship/Won by City Rovers/City Defeats Grafton/North Shore V Newton/Ponsonby V Otahuhu\n| page =8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LIII |issue=16289\n| date = 1916-07-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160724.2.61.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref> City also went on to win the end of season knockout Roope Rooster competition.\n\nOwing to the effects of the war on playing strength there were no representative matches, though [[City Rovers]] did play the Lower Waikato in two exhibition fixtures (home and away), and [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]] and Thames Old Boys (based in Auckland) traveled to [[Thames]] to play a match at the season end.\n\n==End of season report==\nAt the end of the 1916 season a report was made on the season and it was presented to the [[Auckland Rugby League]] annual meeting in May 1917. It stated that the playing ranks had been severely depleted over the past season as over 600 players had joined the ranks of the military to fight in the first world war. There were 42 teams in total to compete across six grades (7 in the senior grade, 5 in second grade, 9 in third grade, 7 in the fourth grade, 8 in the fifth grade, and 6 in the sixth grade). Fourteen clubs were affiliated to the Auckland Rugby League with over 800 players in total. The Mangere, Remuera, and [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote]] clubs withdrew from the competition due to so many of their players going to war.\n\nSignificantly they secured the option of the Chinamen's gardens just off Stanley Street and this was to later be turned into [[Carlaw Park]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Rugby League/Past Season Reviewed\n| page =8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LIV |issue=16526\n| date = 1917-04-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19170430.2.71.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\nIt was suggested that the newly-formed Garrison Artillery Club enter a first grade team however as there were already 6 teams competing there was a fear that it would weaken the existing teams. [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] asked for [[Auckland Rugby League]] to request a special Saturday afternoon \u201ctrain to be run to bring players, spectators and the general public to [[Otahuhu]] or Saturday afternoons\u201d during the season.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Arrangements for Saturday\n| page =4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LIII\n| date = 1916-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160510.2.9.1| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n    {{s-bef|before=[[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|1915]]}}\n    {{s-ttl|title=8th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n    |years=1916}}\n    {{s-aft|after=[[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917]]}}\n    {{end}}\n\n==First grade championship==\nThirty matches were played during the season with the 20 being played at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]]. The Devonport Domain hosted the 5 North Shore Albions home matches, while [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] hosted 5 matches.\n\n===Final Standings and Fixtures===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|10||8||1||1||112||57||'''17'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions]]\n|10||7||1||2||134||57||'''15'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Grafton Athletic]]\n|10||5||0||5||101||85||'''10'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|10||4||1||5||101||86||'''9'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]]\n|10||2||1||6||45||95||'''5'''\n|-\n|style=\"text